study_title: Roadmap Epigenomics Consortium et al. “Integrative Analysis of 111 Reference Human Epigenomes.” Nature 518.7539 (2015): 317–330.
free_text:
Chromatin state discovery and characterization. 

Data were downloaded in R format. We included only intervals overlapping with DNaseI regions selected with -log10(p) >= 10. 

Information about the interpretation of each of the 25 states can be found here: http://egg2.wustl.edu/roadmap/web_portal/imputed.html#chr_imp. 

The name for each cell type can be found here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/u/1/d/1yikGx4MsO9Ei36b64yOy9Vb6oPC5IBGlFbYEt-N6gOM/edit?usp=sharing#gid=15.
Enhancers states included: 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18. Strong enhancers usually defined: 10, 12, 13, 14, 15. 0=no enhancer.
Promoters + TSS states included: 1, 2, 3, 4, 22, 23. Strong promoters + TSS usually defined: 1, 2, 3, 4. 1=TSS, 0=no promoters, TSS.

study_title: Liu, Xiaoming et al. "dbNSFP v3.0: A One-Stop Database of Functional Predictions and Annotations for Human Non-Synonymous and Splice Site SNVs." Human mutation 37.3 (2016): 235-241.
free_text:
Database for Nonsynonymous SNPs' functional predictions, v2.9.3.

The dbNSFP is an integrated database of functional annotations from multiple sources for the comprehensive collection of human non-synonymous SNPs (NSs).

Its current version includes a total of 87,361,054 NSs. It compiles prediction scores from 14 prediction algorithms (SIFT, Polyphen2, LRT, MutationTaster, MutationAssessor, FATHMM, MetaSVM, MetaLR, CADD, VEST, PROVEAN, M-CAP, Eigen\uff0cEigen PC), eight conservation scores (phyloP46way_primate, phyloP46way_placental, phyloP100way_vertebrate, phastCons46way_primate, phastCons46way_placental, phastCons100way_veterbrate, GERP++, and SiPhy) and other function annotations.

We included all the original annotations except for allele frequencies in 1000 genome and ExAC since these are covered in other annotations.

Note 1: Missing data is designated as ".".
Note 2: The three Uniprot entries are based on Polyphen-2 v2.2.2 annotations.

study_title: Fu, Yao et al. “FunSeq2: A Framework for Prioritizing Noncoding Regulatory Variants in Cancer.” Genome Biology 15.10 (2014): 480. PMC. Web. 19 June 2017.
free_text: FUNSEQ 2 is an approach developed for prioritizing somatic cancer mutations.

These files were obtained from UCSC table browser with these settings: Assembly: Feb. 2009 (GRCh37/hg19), Group: Genes and Gene Predictions, Track: GENCODE Genes V19, Region:  genome, Output: format: BED

These gene-level annotations can be used to annotate variants in a VDS by specifying a single gene symbol for each variant. 

This gene key is used to map each variant to the appropriate gene-level annotations.

By default, VEP is run and its output is parsed to extract the gene key (see more detailed description on the bottom of this page).

study_title: Exome Aggregation Consortium et al. "Analysis of Protein-Coding Genetic Variation in 60,706 Humans." Nature 536.7616 (2016): 285-291.
free_text: The Genome Aggregation Database (gnomAD) is a resource developed by an international coalition of investigators, with the goal of aggregating and harmonizing both exome and genome sequencing data from a wide variety of large-scale sequencing projects, and making summary data available for the wider scientific community. The data set provided on this website spans 123,136 exome sequences and 15,496 whole-genome sequences from unrelated individuals sequenced as part of various disease-specific and population genetic studies. The gnomAD Principal Investigators and groups that have contributed data to the current release are listed here.\n\nAll data here are released for the benefit of the wider biomedical community, without restriction on use - see the terms of use here.
Annotations generated from 123,136 whole exome sequences in gnomAD.
Annotations generated from 15,496 whole genome sequences in gnomAD.

study_title: Visel, Axel et al. “VISTA Enhancer Browser—a Database of Tissue-Specific Human Enhancers.” Nucleic Acids Research 35.Database issue (2007): D88–D92.
free_text:
Validated enhancers from VISTA. We select only positive human elements. 

Once downloaded, 2APR2017, the data were processed as follows: 

'grep \">Human\" vista_2APR2017.txt | grep \"positive\" | awk '{split($0,a,\"|\"); print a[2], a[5]}' > vista_2APR2017_processed.txt'

More info available here: https://enhancer.lbl.gov/aboutproject_n.html.
